value.value: The follicle has increased in size considerably but without changing shape. The oocyte occupies >50% to 70% of the length of the follicle.

The follicle has grown further and has become slightly narrower, starting to assume the shape of a mature oocyte. The oocyte occupies 90% of the follicle length. The nurse cells still appear intact and occupy about 10% of the follicle length.

The follicle assumes the shape of the mature oocyte, or almost so, but has not reached full length. The nurse cells have degenerated and at first stain bright crimson with neutral red; later in this stage they disappear. Chorionic structures start to appear.

The oocyte structures its full length. The follicular epithelium degenerates. Chorionic structures such as the floats (Anopheles), micropyle cup (Culex) or surface sculpturing (Aedes) become fully formed.
Attractants are substances that induces gravid females to make oriented movements towards its source.

The juvenile hormone in females of Aedes aegypti increases markedly between 24 and 72h after emergence. Circumstancial evidence associating JH with onset of responsiveness to host cues was obtained with diapausing mosquitoes. Application of large doses of the JH analogue methoprene to diapausing females of Anopheles freeborni and Culex tarsalis hastened their diapause development, including responsiveness to vertebrate hosts.

Juvenile hormones is released after eclosion and stimulates the devlopment of host-seeking behaviour. Little is known about the regulation of juvenile hormone secretion in mosquitoes. Decapitation immediately after emergence has the same effect on follicle development as allatectomy, which suggests that the brain is involved.

definition.value: The mechanism of release of JH after eclosion does not appear to operate in Aedes aegypti. There is evidence from Aedes aegypti of the ovaries affecting JH secretion.

label.value: regulation of follicle growth and competenece

value.value: Two developmental gates control the course of previtellogenic development.
When present, the deterrents (non-volatile substances) inhibit oviposition .

The weight of evidence suggests that gravid females respond negatively to chemical substances emanating from certain predators, but proof of this requires that these substances be isolated, identified and tested as repellents or deterents.
Gravid females make oriented movements away from its source of any oviposition repellent.
Electophysiological analysis of the reflex response showed that the labellar muscles are activated some 40ms after stimulation of the aboral sensilla with sucrose.

label.value: adult response of olfactory sensilla while feeding on plant sugar

value.value: There is some evidence of mosquitoes responding to plant odours in the field.

definition.value: The results were obtained after fine netting bags had been placed over inflorescences of Silene otites (Caryophyllaceae). The experiment was conducted with many variations to prove the responses.

label.value: adult response of olfactory sensilla while host-seeking

value.value: Female mosquitoes respond to host odour (CO2 emission, water vapour, volatiles molecules).
Host odour is here taken to comprise all volatile compounds, organic and inorganic, that emanate from a vertebrate host and that stimulate mosquito chemosensilla.
Short, single walled, multiporous hair sensilla on the antennae of females Aedes, Culex and Anopheles give electrical responses to volatile compounds suspected of being oviposition-site attractants.

definition.value: The sensilla of gravid females showed greater sensitivity to one of these, methyl butyrate, than did those of non-blood-fed females. Non-blood-fed females of Aedes aegypti were unresponsive to methyl propionate vapour in an olfactometer, and females that had blood fed 24h earlier were equally unresponsive. 72-96h after blood feeding they became highly responsive.

value.value: Fatty acids, i.e. saturated and unsaturated monobasic carboxylic acids, when active with gravid females, tended to induce negative responses. Saturated fatty acids from C2 to C11 yielded significant negative responses.
Mosquitoes that belong to this category contain three types of neurones that variously are excited by lactic acid vapour, inhibited by it or unresponsive to it.

label.value: response to chemical cue during pre-oviposition stage and oviposition

value.value: Behavioural responses of the female to chemical stimuli during the stages of pre-oviposition and oviposition.

In nature mosquitoes feed on nectar or blood. Like some other blood-sucking Diptera, usually pass nectar and other plant juices to the crop and dorsal diverticula, but pass blood to the stomach. This separation of nectar and blood permits females to store nectar meal in the crop, passing slowly to the midgut for absorption, while leaving the stomach empty to receive a blood meal at any time.
Stimulants are substances that elicit oviposition.
The responses of mosquitoes to artificial objects have important implications for trap design, but their biological significance is uncertain.
Shade can affect mosquito responses.
Behavioural patterns expressed as a reaction to visual stimuli.

Larvae and pupae that are at the water surface respond to certain stimuli with escape behaviour, often called an alarm response. Usually this takes the form of diving, and at a visibly more rapid rate than in descents made for feeding.

definition.value: Escape behaviour in response to visual stimuli has not been very extensively studied, and the results obtained with some experimental procedures must be reviewed cautiously.

value.value: It is reported that mosquitoes - whether diurnal, crepuscular or nocturnal in activity - fed most often from lighter flowers.

definition.value: White, pink and yellow flowers were attended by mosquitoes when closely adjacent darker flowers were not. Thus white clover (Trifolium repens) and white melilo.

value.value: When the tarsi of a walking mosquito touch a drop of sugar solution the mosquito stops moving or turns, and directs its proboscis towards the stimulus. The tip of the proboskis is placed in contact with the fluid, and when the chemosensory hairs on the aboral surface of the labella are stimulated the labellar lobes spread apart giving the so-called labellar response. Once the labellar lobes have parted, the oral surfaces of the ladella lie flat on the droplet and the external surfaces face away from it. The fluid immediately spreads over the hydrophilic oral surfaces of the labella and their chemosensilla, and over the ligul, submerging the tip of the labrum. When touched by fluid the ligula rapidly increases in size, probably due to a combination of physical forces on the cuticle and internal pressure of haemolymph.
The act of depositing eggs.
Mosquitoes conform with other insects in maintaining lipid and glycogen stores in the fat body. Glycogen is also stored in the flight muscles, and trehalose is stored in the haemolymph.
Anoplines exhibit a variety of oviposition behaviours. None oviposited though while settled on the water surface. A number of anopelines will deposit eggs on moist surfaces.

definition.value: Wild females of Anopheles melas have been observed ovipositing while perched on the vertica surface of pneumatophores in unflooded Avicennia mangover swamps. There has been one report of an anopheline drinking before oviposition (Anopheles messeae). Oviposition without drinking was reported for Anopheles maculipennis sensus stricto and Anopheles atroparvus.

value.value: After a period of flying to and against the roof of the cage, the mosquitoes began to make descents to the floor. Often this was an ordinary diagonal flight movement, but sometimes this descent was a 'pancake landing'.

A female that had touched the water surface changed her mode of flight abruptly, beginning to hover, with little displacement in space. Sometimes she stayed in almost exactly the same spot or bobbed up and down 10mm or so vertically or obliqely, or she might swing through an arc of 20-100mm dipping at each end.

Once arrived at the floor, the mosquitoes flew about at speeds 0,36m/s and at height that usually was 20-40mm. In the course of this horizontal flight they dipped again and again to touch the floor, at spaced intervals varying between 0,06-0,2m. The direction appeared to be random.

label.value: response to optical cue during pre-oviposition stage and oviposition

value.value: The optical cues to which gravid females respond at oviposition sites may come from the water body itself or from its immediate surroundings.

label.value: response to other visual and physical parameters during pre-oviposition stage and oviposition

value.value: For species in which the feeding and resting habitat is different from the oviposition habitat, the gravid females must respond to cues that characterize the 'landscape' before responding to stimuli that characterize specific oviposition sites.

definition.value: Very little is known about the responses of mosquitoes to 'landscape', but it is likely that visual cues are particularly important.

value.value: Chromaticity results from (i)its hue, or dominant wavelengths, and (ii) its chroma (saturation), the extend to which the predominant colour is unadulterated with white. Experiments with females of Aedes aegypti showed that acceptance was low to green and yellow-green, moderate to orange, and high to violet and red.

label.value: response to lightness of the water surface

value.value: Observing that when kept in complete darkness in a roomsized cage females of Culex quinquefasciatus laid in the oviposition dishes provided (dishes which had chemical cues), whereas females of Anopheles darlingi died without ovipositing. De Zalueta (1950) postulated that visual stimuli were essential for egg laying by Andarlingi but not for Culex quinquefasiatus, for which chemical stimuli were more important.

definition.value: Light contrast and dark contrast may both have different causes. The apparent lightness of a body of water may be due to reflection from a pale substratum or to specular reflection from the water surface. A body of water may appear dark relative to its surroundings due to high absorbance by the water or its substratum or to a shielding from incident light.

label.value: response to shade of water surface

value.value: The importance of shade for some species has been demonstrated by its removal. The effect of shade on gravid females is not necessarily direct; for example , it might affect the water temperature of a larval habitat or its chemical composition as a result of leaf fall.

definition.value: Differential responses by egg-laying females of a number of species were revealed by a study of larval densities in a tyre dump, where some tyres were exposed to direct sunlight and others were shaded throughout the entire.

value.value: Dense vegetation is the main physical obstruction. The females of some species must pass through dense vegetation to approach their oviposition sites.

definition.value: The larval habitat of Uranotaenia anhydor at Saratoga Springs, California, was effetively subterranean. Egg rafts and larvae were foun only in pockets of water situated between clumps of the rush Scirpus. These were covered over so densely with mats formed from previous years' growth of rush that the water was in almost darkness.

value.value: The extent of the carbohydrate and lipid reserves and of the protein content of mosquitoes.

The oviposition sites of all ground-water mosquitoes are necessarily at ground-level, but for many species that develop in phytotelmata, the oviposition site is above ground level. This height varies from very moderate to very substantial, the most elevated larval habitats being those of some forest-inhabiting species that live in tree-holes or epiphytic bromeliads.

label.value: response to certain combination of factors

value.value: The responses of gravid females to particular oviposition-site characteristics might change when experienced simultaneously with other characteristics.

definition.value: Pairs of factors to which the responses were compared and contrasted when exposed singly and in combination were: (i)type of surface-open water or moistened filter paper. (ii)Surface texture-rough or smooth, moistened filter paper, affecting olfactory receptors. (iii)Smell-presence or absence of the odour of horse-dung suspension, affecting olfactory receptors. (iv)Salinity-distilled water or 0,086M NaCl, affecting contact chemoreceptors. (v)Lightness- of grey or black filter paper-affecting visual receptors.

value.value: The species Anopheles minimus is known to lay eggs in small, shaded pools adjacent to running water. The females were little influenced by continuous surface ripples.
For its acceptability to gravid females, three characteristics of soil are important, namely: the soil type, the moisture content and the soil texture.

definition.value:
Species of Aedes and Psorophora characteristically deposit their eggs on substrata immediately adjacent to bodies of water or on moist substrata in places subject to inundation.
The importance of the characteristics of a soil surface for its acceptability to gravid females was illustrated by the use of a human-made habitat by 2 flood water mosquitoes, Aedes vexans and Psorophora columbiae.
Survival of the eggs on moist surfaces is an important aspect of anophelines fitness.

value.value: Conversion of the digestion products into glycogen and triacylglycerol deposits.

definition.value: A blood meal can replace nectar as an exogenous energy source.

value.value: Meals of sugar lead to the deposition of glycogen and lipid in the fat body and of glycogen in the flight muscles.
The mechanisms through which sexual behaviour is regulated.

Teneral females are unable to responde to host cues or take a blood meal, but during the first days after emergence their mouthparts and other organs become functional and they develop behavioural capabilities.

label.value: development of competence to respond to host cue

value.value: The development of the capability to respond to a variety of host stimuli.
The differences in responsiveness on host cues observed between virgin and inseminated females in some mosquito species.

definition.value: The flight-activity periodicities of captive females of a number of crepuscular/nocturnal species changed, and came to resemble the periodicities of man-biting activity in wild populations. One effect is on the phase of the flight-activity rhythm. It is suggested that a factor in the semen of the males of the autogenous strains suppressed blood-feeding by the nulliparous females of these strains. In some species, virgin females are less responsive to host cues than inseminated females. Another effect is the inhibition of responsiveness to host cues in females due to male accessory-gland secretion.
